[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 is stable at 212. This includes 19 countries (including 4 territories) from the Western Pacific region, 60 countries (including 7 territories) from the European region, 10 from the Southeast Asia region, 22 countries (including 1 territory) from the Eastern Mediterranean region, 54 countries (including 19 territories) from the Americas region, and 47 countries (including 2 territories) from the African region.

The Americas region is reporting 37 589 (46.3% of the total newly reported cases) new cases (in the past 24 hours) of which 79.9%% were reported by the USA, followed by Brazil at 8.7%, and Canada (4.6%). Recognizing the USA data are overshadowing the regional proportions, without including the reported newly confirmed cases from the USA, Brazil reported 43.4% of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Canada at 23.0%, Mexico, and Chile both at 7.6%.

The European region newly confirmed 35 300 (43.5% of the global newly reported cases) new cases and 3737 (57.8%) deaths in the 24 hours since the last WHO update. Russia accounted for 17.2% of newly confirmed cases in the region, followed by the UK with 15.7%, Turkey with 10.7%, Spain with 10.4%, Italy 9.9%, France 7.2%, and Germany 7.0%. These 7 countries, accounting for 11.7% of the countries in the European region, reported 78.0% of the newly confirmed cases.

In the Eastern Mediterranean region, Iran reported 1374 new cases representing 34.3% of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Saudi Arabia at 28.2%, Pakistan at 12.8%, and Qatar at 8.6% (the United Arab Emirate did not report any cases in the past 24 hours).

In the African region, there were 25 countries reporting no cases in this 24 hour period. That being said, South Africa reported 31.9% of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ghana at 24.5%, Algeria at 14.7%, and Guinea at 4.9%.

In the Western Pacific region, Japan reported 39.3% of the newly reported cases, followed by Singapore at 36.3%, the Philippines 14.5%, and Malaysia and Australia each at 3.7%.

In South East Asia, India reported 65.8% of newly reported cases, followed by Indonesia at 16.0% and Bangladesh at 15.1%. Removing India from the denominator, Indonesia represents 46.8% of the newly reported cases, Bangladesh 44.1%, Thailand 4.6%, and Myanmar 1.9%.

Figure 2. Epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases, by date of report and WHO region through [19 Apr 2020], at the source URL above, is an excellent representation of the epidemic starting in the Western Pacific, transitioning to multiregional activity as the virus travelled. One sees the contribution of the ongoing epidemics in Europe and now the increasing cases in the Americas region, fueled by the USA but other countries are following suit. The curve tends to drop over the weekends, but it hasn't really done so this weekend, although the America's region did not appear to drop.

A somewhat repetitive but necessary reminder: it is clear that the number of reported confirmed cases differs from different reporting websites and is somewhat a function of time of day the website is updated. For example, I note the time we've accessed the Johns Hopkin's CSSE or Worldometer website, but by the time the post is actually finished with the editing process, those numbers have at times significantly changed. Case counting is clearly a moving target, and, depending upon when the website updates, the numbers may be different. I try to start each post with the latest figures for the calendar day (the John Hopkins CSSE and Worldometer table) and close with the figures from the start of the calendar day (the WHO tables), defining the calendar day as DST (now GMT-4).

For the past 4 weeks, I have had help compiling all of the data presented in the tables and preparing spreadsheets, and want to publicly thank Coleman Schaefer for his amazing assistance -- a formidable task to say the least. - Mod.MPP]
